    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Limitation of a Single Head"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A single attention head computes one weighted blend of value vectors per position. For a given query, it can only represent one set of attention weights — one \"opinion\" about which tokens to aggregate. Natural language regularly demands more than one simultaneous perspective: a word may need to track its grammatical subject, its semantic object, and its local phrase context all at once. A single head must spread its weight budget across all these needs, which dilutes every signal."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Subspace Diversity"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each head projects the input into a different "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "d_k-dimensional subspace"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " of the original d_model space. The key insight is that heads are not given fixed roles — they discover which subspace is most useful through gradient descent. In practice they converge to different structural roles because it is more efficient to specialise than to generalize."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Comparison of a single head spreading attention thinly vs three specialised heads each capturing a distinct relationship for the token 'saw'"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Free Lunch Argument"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using h heads of dimension d_k = d_model/h has the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "same total parameter count"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " as one head of dimension d_model. The split costs nothing in parameters; it only changes how the capacity is allocated. Yet empirically the multi-head version outperforms the single-head equivalent because it can represent multiple independent attention distributions simultaneously."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\underbrace{h \\cdot 3 \\cdot d_{\\text{model}} \\cdot d_k}_{\\text{all Q,K,V for }h\\text{ heads}} + \\underbrace{d_{\\text{model}}^2}_{W_O} = 4 d_{\\text{model}}^2 \\quad \\text{(same as 1 head at } d_k = d_{\\text{model}}\\text{)}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Empirical Evidence: What Heads Learn"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Analysis of trained BERT and GPT models (Clark et al. 2019, Voita et al. 2019) consistently identifies heads that specialise in distinct patterns:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Syntactic heads:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " track subject–verb dependencies and noun–modifier relationships. Removing them degrades POS-tagging probes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Coreference heads:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " route pronoun tokens back to their antecedents. Important for tasks like Winograd schema."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Positional heads:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " attend to the immediately preceding or following token — functioning like a learned n-gram filter."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Rare-token heads:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " strongly attend to rare or unexpected tokens, routing surprising information up the network."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Measuring Head Importance: Ablation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A simple way to measure how much a head contributes is to zero out its output and observe the performance drop:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification\nimport torch\n\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased')\nmodel = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(\n    'bert-base-uncased', num_labels=2)\nmodel.eval()\n\ntext = \"The food was great but the service was slow.\"\ninputs = tokenizer(text, return_tensors='pt')\n\n# Baseline logits\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    baseline = model(**inputs).logits\n\n# Ablate head 3 in layer 0 by zeroing its output projection rows\ndef ablate_head(model, layer_idx, head_idx):\n    d_model = model.config.hidden_size\n    h = model.config.num_attention_heads\n    d_k = d_model // h\n    # W_O: (d_model, d_model); rows [head_idx*d_k : (head_idx+1)*d_k] correspond to head\n    out_proj = model.bert.encoder.layer[layer_idx].attention.self.value\n    # Zero the value projection for this head instead (simpler)\n    with torch.no_grad():\n        start, end = head_idx * d_k, (head_idx + 1) * d_k\n        out_proj.weight[start:end, :].zero_()\n    return model\n\nablated_model = ablate_head(model, layer_idx=0, head_idx=3)\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    ablated = ablated_model(**inputs).logits\n\nprint(\"Baseline logits: \", baseline)\nprint(\"Ablated logits:  \", ablated)\nprint(\"Change:          \", (ablated - baseline).abs().mean().item())"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Head Pruning: Many Heads Are Redundant"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Voita et al. (2019) showed that in BERT, the majority of heads can be "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "pruned without measurable accuracy loss"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". A small number of heads per layer carry most of the task-relevant signal; the rest provide redundancy or specialise in rare phenomena. This finding motivated structured pruning methods and smaller architectures."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Conceptual: prune heads with lowest gradient-based importance score\nimport torch\nfrom transformers import AutoModelForSequenceClassification, AutoTokenizer\n\nmodel = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=2)\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased')\n\n# HuggingFace supports head masking natively:\n# head_mask: (num_layers, num_heads) tensor of 0/1\nnum_layers = model.config.num_hidden_layers\nnum_heads  = model.config.num_attention_heads\n\n# Zero out head 4 in layer 2 and head 7 in layer 5\nhead_mask = torch.ones(num_layers, num_heads)\nhead_mask[2, 4] = 0.0\nhead_mask[5, 7] = 0.0\n\ninputs = tokenizer(\"Example sentence.\", return_tensors='pt')\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    out = model(**inputs, head_mask=head_mask)\nprint(out.logits)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Optimal Number of Heads"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Head count is a hyperparameter. Too few heads under-represents the diversity of linguistic relationships; too many heads each get so few dimensions (d_k = d_model/h) that they lack the capacity to represent complex patterns. Common choices:"
          }
        ]
      },
