      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Across architectures, d_k = 64 or 128 is common — small enough to be fast, large enough for meaningful patterns. The number of heads scales with model size, maintaining the ratio."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Key insight:"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " Multiple heads are not just an engineering trick — they are why transformers can represent the full combinatorial richness of language. Each head attends to the same sequence but in a different subspace, so the final W_O-combined representation carries information about many relationship types at once."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
